Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[A fascinating description of the studies of the passengers and crew on the now infamous Diamond Princess that was quarantined for 14+ days off Yokohama after it was learned that a passenger who had left the ship in Hong Kong, had tested positive for the SARS-CoV-2 (see prior ProMED-mail posts during the period 4-20 Feb 2020).

Note that 410 asymptomatic infections were identified, with 79 (19.3%) converting to symptomatic infections during the follow up period and were reclassified as pre-symptomatic infections. In total 311 (75.9%) of the asymptomatic infected individuals remained asymptomatic after complete follow up (a number of the PCR negative individuals were repatriated and were found to be PCR positive upon return to their home countries). This study focused on the 96 asymptomatic infections and their PCR negative cabinmates. The fascinating finding was the infection clearance rate most associated with age of infected individual -- the older the individual the longer it took to have a PCR negative test indicative of resolved infection. That being said, viral cultures were not done which would have identified those with prolonged infections with viable transmissible viruses vs those with persistent viral debris leaving genetic material behind.

Supplemental background, tables, and figures can be found at https://www.nejm.org/doi/suppl/10.1056/NEJMc2013020/suppl_file/nejmc2013020_appendix.pdf

Maps of Japan can be seen at https://geology.com/world/japan-satellite-image.shtml and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7496025,65331. Yokohama is just south of Tokyo. - Mod.MPP]

