B. Viet Nam: asymptomatic infections and transmission, CID
Date: Thu 4 Jun 2020
Source: Clinical Infectious Disease [edited]
https://academic.oup.com/cid/advance-article/doi/10.1093/cid/ciaa711/5851471


Chau NVV, Thanh Lam V, Thanh Dung N, et al. The natural history and transmission potential of asymptomatic SARS-CoV-2 infection [published online ahead of print, 2020 Jun 4]. Clin Infect Dis. 2020;ciaa711. doi:10.1093/cid/ciaa711
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Abstract
--------
Background
Little is known about the natural history of asymptomatic SARS-CoV-2 infection or its contribution to infection transmission.

Methods
We conducted a prospective study at a quarantine center for COVID-19 in Ho Chi Minh City, Viet Nam. We enrolled quarantined people with RT-PCR-confirmed SARS-CoV-2 infection, collecting clinical data, travel and contact history, and saliva at enrolment and daily nasopharyngeal throat swabs (NTS) for RT-PCR testing. We compared the natural history and transmission potential of asymptomatic and symptomatic individuals.

Results
Between [10 Mar 2020] and [4 Apr 2020], 14 000 quarantined people were tested for SARS-CoV-2; 49 were positive. Of these, 30 participated in the study: 13 (43%) never had symptoms and 17 (57%) were symptomatic. 17 (57%) participants acquired their infection outside Viet Nam. Compared with symptomatic individuals, asymptomatic people were less likely to have detectable SARS-CoV-2 in NTS samples collected at enrolment (8/13 (62%) vs. 17/17 (100%) P=0.02). SARS-CoV-2 RNA was detected in 20/27 (74%) available saliva; 7/11 (64%) in the asymptomatic and 13/16 (81%) in the symptomatic group (P=0.56). Analysis of the probability of RT-PCR positivity showed asymptomatic participants had faster viral clearance than symptomatic participants (P less than 0.001 for difference over 1st 19 days). This difference was most pronounced during the 1st week of follow up. 2 of the asymptomatic individuals appeared to transmit the infection to up to 4 contacts.

Conclusions
Asymptomatic SARS-CoV-2 infection is common and can be detected by analysis of saliva or NTS. NTS viral loads fall faster in asymptomatic individuals, but they appear able to transmit the virus to others.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[While the numbers in this study are small, the cited percentage of asymptomatic infections among contacts of SARS-CoV2 positive cases is an impressive 43%. The suggestion that 2 of the asymptomatic infected individuals may have transmitted the virus to as many as 4 individuals (an R0 of 2.0) is consistent with the speculation that the asymptomatic infected individuals are the secret weapon of this virus to behave in a stealth manner and make identifying chains of transmission difficult in the early stages of the outbreaks in locations around the world, including in the original outbreak in Wuhan, but also in Iran, Italy, Spain, the USA. In the early stages of the outbreak, only symptomatic individuals were tested, including symptomatic contacts, leaving a significant number of asymptomatic infected individuals to continue the chains of transmission under the radarscope. As the authors stress in their discussion, the testing and quarantining of all identified contacts is critical for ultimately interrupting the chains of transmission of this virus.

Maps of Viet Nam can be seen at https://geology.com/world/vietnam-satellite-image.shtml and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7496025,152. - Mod.MPP]

