[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 215.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:
-----------------------------------------
The Americas region reported 63.4% of the global newly reported cases and 68.3% of newly reported deaths for this 24-hour period. Brazil reported 47.2% of the newly confirmed cases in the region, the USA reported 31.6%, Chile 4.6%, Mexico 4.3%, and Peru 3.0%. The same 5 countries remained at the top, with Brazil switching place with the USA.

The European region reported 9.8% of the global newly reported cases and 9.3% of the newly confirmed deaths in the region. Russia reported 43.1% of the regional newly reported cases, followed by the UK 7.2%, Turkey 7.0%, Ukraine 4.1%, Germany 3.8%, and Belarus 3.4%. Again, same countries, minor juggling of orders and percentages day by day (Germany and Belarus switched places).

The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 10.4% of the global newly reported cases and 10.9% of global newly reported fatalities. Pakistan reported 26.1% of the regional newly reported cases followed by Saudi Arabia 20.8%, Iran 12.2%, Iraq 9.9%, Egypt 8.2%, Qatar 5.4%, and Oman 4.7%. Same countries, minor juggling of positions (Iraq and Egypt switched places).

The African region reported 4.6% of the global newly reported cases and 2.6% of newly reported fatalities. South Africa reported 58.7% of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Nigeria 7.8%, Ghana 6.1%, Cote d'Ivoire and Ethiopia at 4.7% each, Central African Republic 2.4%, and Congo DR and Mauritania at 2.3% each. While South Africa and Nigeria are consistently numbers 1 and 2 in terms of the 24-hour increase in cases, other countries have less consistent reporting patterns and vary considerably from day to day (Cameroon was number 2 yesterday, 20 Jun 2020, and today reported 0 newly confirmed cases).

The Western Pacific region reported 0.75% of the global newly reported cases and 0.46% of global deaths. The Philippines reported 68.7% of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Singapore 15.9%, Japan 4.7%, South Korea 3.5%, and China and Australia 2.0% each. The outbreak associated with the Beijing Seafood markets continues to bring China to prominence in terms of daily newly confirmed cases. That said, the Philippines and Singapore are consistently numbers 1 and 2, respectively, and the other countries, including Malaysia and Australia, vary in daily reporting.

The South East Asia region reported 11.1% of the global newly reported cases and 8.4% of global deaths. India reported 76.1% of newly reported cases in the region, followed by Bangladesh 16.0%, Indonesia 6.1%, and Nepal 1.6%. Same countries, same order as in previous days.

Impression: Europe seems to be stabilizing at a significantly lower rate, although Russia is still reporting 7000+ new cases a day (down from 8000+ per day). The Eastern Mediterranean has surpassed the European region, with Pakistan reporting around 4000+ cases a day and Saudi Arabia reporting around 4000+ cases a day. South East Asia has overtaken both the European and Eastern Mediterranean regions, with India reporting 8000-10 000+ cases a day (over 15 000 cases today 21 Jun 2020). The Americas region is usually reporting around 70 000 cases a day (over 100 000 cases today 21 Jun 2020), with Brazil usually reporting 25 000-30 000+ cases a day (over 50 000 cases today 21 Jun 2020) and the USA at 20 000-25 000+ a day (over 30 000 today 21 Jun 2020). In the Africa region, the regional proportion is slowly climbing, with South Africa reporting in the 3000-4000+ range daily, and the Western Pacific region is maintaining a very low rate compared with the other regions, with the Philippines averaging 500+ cases per day (over 900 cases today 21 Jun 2020). (Singapore had been reporting twice as many cases per day for a period of time but has dropped back over the past couple of weeks).

Figure 2. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases, by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 21 Jun 2020, at the source URL above, is an excellent representation of the epidemic starting in the Western Pacific, transitioning to multiregional activity as the virus travelled. Europe has significantly decreased. The Americas region continues to increase, as does South East Asia, which overtook the Eastern Mediterranean and European regions today [20 Jun 2020] in terms of daily newly confirmed cases; the African region is noticeably increasing as well. The Americas region continues to greatly outnumber all other regions for daily reporting. - Mod.MPP]

